1. The organization is as follows:
	zxy@debian:~/workspace/30Gsda5/myproject$ tree
	.
	笏懌楳笏 app
	笏つﾂ 笏懌楳笏 Makefile
	笏つﾂ 笏披楳笏 sensor_tool.c
	笏懌楳笏 driver
	笏つﾂ 笏懌楳笏 inc
	笏つﾂ 笏つﾂ 笏披楳笏 mysensor_ioctl.h
	笏つﾂ 笏懌楳笏 Makefile
	笏つﾂ 笏披楳笏 src
	笏つﾂ     笏懌楳笏 fakesensor.c
	笏つﾂ     笏懌楳笏 fakesensor.h
	笏つﾂ     笏披楳笏 mysensordrv.c
	笏披楳笏 README
   The app is mainly for test the dirver

2. For driver: 
       <a>make -C driver 
       <b>make -C driver test=1
       <c>make -C driver format
       <d>make -C clean
   <a>: To make the .ko driver target.
   <b>: To test the dirver, besides making driver .ko file, this will automatically generate 2 devices matching the driver under /dev, named /dev/mychardev0, /dev/mychardev1
   <c>: To format the src code of the driver if clang-format is installed
   <d>: To clean the outputs.

3. To make app, run
       make -C app
   To clean app, run
       make -C app clean
   App usage:
	zxy@debian:~/workspace/30Gsda5/myproject/app$ ./sensor-cli 
	Usage:
	  ./sensor-cli <dev> get_status
	  ./sensor-cli <dev> get_temp
	  ./sensor-cli <dev> get_humidity
	  ./sensor-cli <dev> get_threshold
	  ./sensor-cli <dev> get_alarm
	  ./sensor-cli <dev> set_temp <value>
	  ./sensor-cli <dev> set_humidity <value>
	  ./sensor-cli <dev> set_threshold <value>
	  ./sensor-cli <dev> clear_alarm
	  ./sensor-cli <dev> trigger_alarm
	  ./sensor-cli <dev> wait_alarm
	  ./sensor-cli <dev> wait_alarm_timeout <ms>

	Example:
	  ./sensor-cli /dev/mychardev0 get_status
	  ./sensor-cli /dev/mychardev0 set_temp 88
	  ./sensor-cli /dev/mychardev0 wait_alarm
	  ./sensor-cli /dev/mychardev0 wait_alarm_timeout 5000
	zxy@debian:~/workspace/30Gsda5/myproject/app$ 


4. build kernel step, in build-root
<0> preparation, run
	zxy@debian:~/workspace/30Gsda5/buildroot$ qemu-system-arm -machine help
	Supported machines are:
	ast1030-evb          Aspeed AST1030 MiniBMC (Cortex-M4)
	ast2500-evb          Aspeed AST2500 EVB (ARM1176)
	ast2600-evb          Aspeed AST2600 EVB (Cortex-A7)
	.....
	zxy@debian:~/workspace/30Gsda5/buildroot$ 
    to select a platform and we will modify the dfs of it.
    We choose ast2600-evb
<1> At the root dir of build root run
	make menuconfig
    to build rootfs, do not select kernel, just build rootfs first. Pay attention to the platform, use the information of <0>, for example:
        Target Architecture (ARM (little endian))  --->
        Target Architecture Variant (cortex-A7)  --->
        Target ABI (EABIhf)  --->  
        Floating point strategy (VFPv4-D16)  --->
        ARM instruction set (ARM)  --->
        Target Binary Format (ELF)  --->     
<2> run make to build rootfs
<3> make menuconfig, select kernel and select kernel config to default, see Kernel configuration in step <5>
<4> make linux-menuconfig to modify the config, mainly to decrease the time to make kernel. I supplyed the .config with which I tested my driver. So can use this directly from step <5>.
<5> copy the generated linux kernel output/build/linux-6.19.3/.config to buildroot root dir, and make menuconfig to select the config file, for example:
     [*] Linux Kernel                                                                                   
         Kernel version (Latest version (6.19))  --->                                               
         ()    Custom kernel patches                                                                      
         Kernel configuration (Using a custom (def)config file)  --->                                
         (./arm32_config.txt) Configuration file path                                                     
         ()    Additional configuration fragment files                                                    
         ()    Custom boot logo file path                                                                 
               Kernel binary format (zImage)  --->                  
<6>  make linux-rebuild to build the kernel.

5. We will now modify the kernel to inject our driver.
<1> The step to modify kernel src can be found in the mysecure/README of this repo, we only give the Makefile of the module
	zxy@debian:~/workspace/30Gsda5/buildroot/output/build/linux-6.19.3/drivers/mysensor$ pwd
	/home/zxy/workspace/30Gsda5/buildroot/output/build/linux-6.19.3/drivers/mysensor
	zxy@debian:~/workspace/30Gsda5/buildroot/output/build/linux-6.19.3/drivers/mysensor$ ls
	built-in.a  inc  Kconfig  Makefile  modules.order  src
	zxy@debian:~/workspace/30Gsda5/buildroot/output/build/linux-6.19.3/drivers/mysensor$ cat Makefile 
	obj-$(CONFIG_MYSENSOR) += mysensor.o
	ccflags-y += -I$(src)/inc -I$(src)/src
	mysensor-y := src/mysensordrv.o src/fakesensor.o

	zxy@debian:~/workspace/30Gsda5/buildroot/output/build/linux-6.19.3/drivers/mysensor$ 
	zxy@debian:~/workspace/30Gsda5/buildroot/output/build/linux-6.19.3/drivers/mysensor$ cat Kconfig 
	menu "MYSENSOR support"
	config MYSENSOR
		tristate "MYSENSOR Support"
		default y
		help
		Say Y to enable MYSENSOR support, M to compile it as a module
	endmenu
	zxy@debian:~/workspace/30Gsda5/buildroot/output/build/linux-6.19.3/drivers/mysensor$ 
<2> At build-root root dir, run make linux-menuconfig to confirm the menu of MYSENSOR appears.
<3> Run make linux-rebuild to make our new kernel.
<4> Modify the dtsi(arch/arm/boot/dts/aspeed/aspeed-ast2600-evb.dts at linux root dir) as follows:
	......
        vcc_sdhci0: regulator-vcc-sdhci0 {
                compatible = "regulator-fixed";
                regulator-name = "SDHCI0 Vcc";
                regulator-min-microvolt = <3300000>;
                regulator-max-microvolt = <3300000>;
                gpios = <&gpio0 ASPEED_GPIO(V, 0) GPIO_ACTIVE
_HIGH>;
                enable-active-high;
        };

        mysensor: zxysensor {
                compatible = "zxy,fakesensor";
        };
	.....
       I supplyed the dts I used to test my driver.
<5> At linux kernel src dir(output/build/linux-6.19.3), first run
	export PATH=~/workspace/30Gsda5/buildroot/output/host/bin:$PATH
    to add build root toolchain, then run
	make ARCH=arm CROSS_COMPILE=arm-buildroot-linux-gnueabihf- aspeed/aspeed-ast2600-evb.dtb 
    to build the new dtb
<6> Use command
	qemu-system-arm   -M ast2600-evb   -m 1024   -nographic   -kernel output/images/zImage   -dtb output/build/linux-6.19.3/arch/arm/boot/dts/aspeed/aspeed-ast2600-evb.dtb   -initrd output/images/rootfs.cpio   -append "console=ttyS4,115200 rdinit=/sbin/init"
    To boot the machine.
<7> The machine will not mount devtempfs by default ,run below command to see our device is working well:
	Welcome to Buildroot
	buildroot login: root
